This looks like a mistake:

``` lang-java
executor.shutdown();
        
while(executor.isTerminated()) {
    System.out.println(&quot;Terminating Thread-&quot;+Thread.currentThread().getName());
}
```

The `while` loop probably is going to do _nothing._ Your tasks have only just been started by the time it calls [`isTerminated()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/ExecutorService.html#isShutdown()). The `isTerminated()` probably will return `false`, and you&#39;ll drop out of the loop without ever printing anything.

If you get unlucky, and _all_ of the tasks have completed by the time you get to the `isTerminated()` test, then `isTerminated()` will return `true`, _forever,_ and your program will get stuck, printing the same message again and again, _forever._

You probably meant to say, `while(! executor.isTerminated()) {...}`

----------------

**But Wait!**

There&#39;s a better way. You probably don&#39;t want those while loops to print again and again _until_ the executors shut down either. Instead of [_polling_]() to await the completion of the tasks, why not call [`awaitTermination`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/ExecutorService.html#awaitTermination(long,java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit)), and then just print _one_ message instead?


``` lang-java
executor.shutdown();
try {
    executor.awaitTermination(10000, TimeUnit.DAYS);
} catch (InterruptedException ex) {
    ...handle exception according to the needs of your application...
}   
System.out.println(&quot;All tasks completed&quot;);}
```

-----------------------------

This _might_ also be a mistake (Only you can say for sure):

``` lang-java
System.out.println(&quot;Terminating Thread-&quot;+Thread.currentThread().getName());
```

The message kind of looks as if you expect it to print the name of a thread that it&#39;s waiting for. But, what it actually will print is the name of the thread that&#39;s doing the waiting. Is that what you wanted?

